0bb0e4cfd8e58924816f59b438b15beef0849fad23541aec50fa2","event_uuid":"d0dfe210-11d8-4f78-8302-40216a19f8e3","position":{"commit_sha":"5aaffa5bdc5fe65611953487060f15f57aac0db6","position":"1784320476519446001-d0dfe210-11d8-4f78-8302-40216a19f8e3"},"signature":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","signer_pubkey":"ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHe3p+OG3L79IIh99qRBEkAEXaU+VbeQcSfhIu4M2F8b rebar-bot joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com"},{"content_hash":"c6ab9ef272f7ff3653f161fa350d922950366ad8cb118902ad9dcca8e2c7c467","event_uuid":"585a252b-49d5-413d-81c9-cf006e6e5aef","position":{"commit_sha":"249d0fc0936061a7a02b5d9929523b7adc4fee45","position":"1784329417042887001-585a252b-49d5-413d-81c9-cf006e6e5aef"},"signature":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","signer_pubkey":"ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHe3p+OG3L79IIh99qRBEkAEXaU+VbeQcSfhIu4M2F8b rebar-bot joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com"},{"content_hash":"e40a0312dbe9d31fc21c3ba9ae29f86eea32663aac428f2159f382dc625190d1","event_uuid":"b801db19-05c0-41f4-9714-362f7e7eb846","position":{"commit_sha":"de013dd6f7ab488d89c5decde6a8a338ba24684d","position":"1784329419948733001-b801db19-05c0-41f4-9714-362f7e7eb846"},"signature":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","signer_pubkey":"ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHe3p+OG3L79IIh99qRBEkAEXaU+VbeQcSfhIu4M2F8b rebar-bot joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com"},{"content_hash":"1dafe8b88743a8bf62d8a4d118a9e651d2013048b4a71961530b4ea0a226b728","event_uuid":"8eb931d6-6f6b-413c-9906-e661b5d377c1","position":{"commit_sha":"ac7e35af13b66074fb37c2756d04d985f461bf5e","position":"1784330204373458001-8eb931d6-6f6b-413c-9906-e661b5d377c1"},"signature":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","signer_pubkey":"ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIHe3p+OG3L79IIh99qRBEkAEXaU+VbeQcSfhIu4M2F8b rebar-bot joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com"}],"bridge_alerts":[],"claim_harness":null,"claim_remote_session":null,"claimed_session":null,"comments":[{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","body":"Planning decomposition is complete and intentionally remains open/unclaimed until implementation begins.\n\nHierarchy and order:\n\n- `2c14-fa5f-1228-4e02` — complete the generic code-review project-criterion runtime seam.\n  - `8a4b-e8b6-1bf9-48d8` — reproduce and repair the integration defect.\n- `225a-323c-a9f6-436b` — author `project.review-phase-boundaries` and its balanced eval corpus; depends on `2c14`.\n- `9447-b31c-e0b7-446d` — run the live Gerrit dogfood probe; depends on both `2c14` and `225a`.\n\nThe seam defect is verified in the current code: project routing can describe a code-review criterion, but Round-A fan-in does not dynamically execute activated project prompts; eval/CLI resolution is plan-review-biased and the code-review solver admits a closed prompt set; Pass 3 does not consistently consume one repository-effective routing view. The bug owns a generic, gate-keyed repair with no `project.review-phase-boundaries` special case.\n\nRollout remains advisory-only: `block_threshold: 0.90`, `blocking_enabled: false`. Existing `suggested_fix` support is grandfathered debt; unchanged uses are ignored and new/expanded Pass-1 remediation is a violation. A future blocking promotion requires a separate reviewed ticket backed by accumulated Gerrit evidence.","timestamp":1784329419948733001}],"created_at":1783791415033392218,"creation_channel":"jira","creation_channel_inferred":true,"deps":[],"description":"## Context\n\nrebar's reusable review system intentionally separates four concerns: a critical finder discovers\ncandidate issues, a generous verifier independently assesses those candidates, deterministic policy\ndecides their disposition, and a coach helps the client respond without taking over remediation.\nCriteria calibration regularly erodes those boundaries by moving severity, disposition, or fix\ninstructions into the finder; similar drift can make the verifier invent issues, the decision phase\ndepend on an LLM, or the coach re-adjudicate results.\n\nThis epic dogfoods the existing project-criteria extension described by ADRs 0015, 0016, and 0017.\nThe boundary policy remains a project-owned criterion rather than a packaged rebar-core criterion.\nOne generic core bug is included because inspection of `origin/main` found that the advertised\ncode-review extension seam is incomplete: project routing can merge, but a net-new LLM-backed\nproject criterion is not dynamically fanned into Pass 1, resolved by the eval surface, or consulted\nthrough repository-aware routing in Pass 3.\n\n## Why\n\nSeparation creates productive tension: Pass 1 is intentionally critical while Pass 2 is\nintentionally generous, and Pass 4 separates the reviewer from the client who owns remediation.\nLetting one phase perform another phase's job collapses that tension, makes review outcomes harder\nto reason about, and turns rubric edits into hidden policy changes.\n\nThe chosen approach adds one co-located project criterion, `project.review-phase-boundaries`, rather\nthan one criterion per phase. This gives the code-review gate one architectural invariant to invoke\nand one balanced eval corpus to calibrate while preserving precise phase-specific subrules.\n\n## Four-Phase Contract\n\n- **Pass 1 — discover:** emit evidence-grounded candidate findings only. Refining which problems a\n  criterion discovers, or the evidence required for discovery, is valid. Assessing validity,\n  impact, severity, confidence, drop/block posture, or remediation is a boundary violation.\n- **Pass 2 — assess:** answer atomic binary validity and impact questions for an existing candidate\n  only. It does not discover new findings, decide disposition, or prescribe a fix.\n- **Pass 3 — decide:** apply configured thresholds and deterministic rules to drop, block, or retain\n  findings. No LLM participates and no new evidence or coaching is introduced.\n- **Pass 4 — coach:** provide non-prescriptive next-move guidance for already-decided blocking and\n  non-blocking findings. It does not re-verify, change disposition, or dictate an exact\n  implementation.\n\nExisting `suggested_fix` support is grandfathered debt: unchanged occurrences are not findings, new\nor expanded Pass-1 remediation directives are findings, and the field is removed the next time its\ncore contract is otherwise touched rather than expanding this epic into an unrelated migration.\n\n## Scope\n\n1. **Complete the generic integration seam — `2c14-fa5f-1228-4e02`:** deliver dynamic fan-in,\n   repository-effective Pass-3 routing, project eval/CLI resolution, compatibility coverage, and\n   runtime documentation. Its child bug `8a4b-e8b6-1bf9-48d8` owns the reproduced defect and fix.\n   The repair maps logical `project.<name>` ids to validator-safe physical\n   `code-review-project-<name>` ids and adds no `project.review-phase-boundaries` special case.\n   Routing JSON remains keyed by the logical id; physical ids exist only at prompt/eval dispatch.\n2. **Author the project criterion — `225a-323c-a9f6-436b`:** add project routing, prompt, tests, and a\n   balanced `RP-F1..RP-F6` / `RP-N1..RP-N6` eval corpus. Configure `block_threshold: 0.90` but keep\n   `blocking_enabled: false`.\n3. **Dogfood in Gerrit — `9447-b31c-e0b7-446d`:** capture a valid positive control and an invalid\n   cross-phase directive in real advisory-only reviews, including Pass-2 and Pass-3 evidence; amend\n   the invalid directive out before submission.\n\nWork is sequential: the seam story and nested bug precede criterion authoring, and both precede\nlive Gerrit dogfooding. The dogfood story also directly depends on the seam story so the runtime\nprerequisite is visible even if the criterion story is later reorganized.\n\nOut of scope: enabling blocking, tuning the `0.90` threshold without real-review data, changing the\nkernel's impact model or deterministic decision math, modifying packaged built-in criteria, or\nremoving untouched `suggested_fix` debt. Any future promotion to `blocking_enabled: true` requires a\nseparate ticket whose plan cites accumulated Gerrit evidence.\n\n## Risks and Rollout\n\n- **False positives from policy prose or examples:** require an operative instruction, identifiable\n  phase ownership, negative-example suppression, and abstention when ownership is unclear; prove the\n  distinction with the balanced eval corpus before live rollout.\n- **Extension seam changes regress repositories without overlays:** preserve the overlay-absent path\n  and pin it with compatibility tests in the seam bug.\n- **Premature contributor blocking:** ship and dogfood with `blocking_enabled: false`; the configured\n  `0.90` threshold is observational until a separately reviewed, data-backed posture change.\n- **A known-bad probe lands:** use a real intermediate Gerrit patchset for evidence, then remove the\n  directive and record the final phase-compliant revision before submission.\n\nRollback is additive: revert the project routing/prompt/eval assets to disable the criterion, and\nrevert the generic fan-in/routing/eval repair as one unit if its compatibility suite regresses. No\nticket-store or user-data migration is involved.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A net-new project code-review criterion executes end to end through all four passes without a\n  project-specific branch in rebar core.\n- The project criterion fails changes that move assessment, deterministic disposition, or\n  remediation across phase boundaries and passes changes that only refine a phase's owned concern.\n- Offline evals discriminate all twelve required cases, and live Gerrit evidence covers both a\n  valid refinement and an invalid directive.\n- The entire pilot remains advisory; blocking posture is deferred until real dogfood data supports\n  a separate decision.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The three direct child stories `2c14-fa5f-1228-4e02`, `225a-323c-a9f6-436b`, and\n  `9447-b31c-e0b7-446d` plus nested seam bug `8a4b-e8b6-1bf9-48d8` are closed; verify hierarchy and\n  status with\n  `.venv/bin/rebar list --parent jira-reb-1001 --output llm`,\n  `.venv/bin/rebar list --parent 2c14-fa5f-1228-4e02 --output llm`.\n- [ ] The bug, criterion, and dogfood changes are landed on `main`; verify commits with\n  `git log origin/main --oneline --grep='rebar-ticket: \\(8a4b-e8b6-1bf9-48d8\\|225a-323c-a9f6-436b\\|9447-b31c-e0b7-446d\\)'`.\n- [ ] The generic seam accepts a synthetic activated code-review `project.*` criterion, runs its\n  physical prompt exactly once in Pass 1, resolves its diff-based eval spec through the existing\n  code-review solver arm, and rejects unknown/inactive ids at the CLI; verify with\n  `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_code_review_project_criteria.py`.\n- [ ] Pass 3 uses repository-effective threshold, posture, and nit-suppression values for the\n  synthetic logical id while an overlay-absent repository preserves its pre-change result; verify\n  with `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_code_review_project_criteria.py -k 'routing or parity'`.\n- [ ] `project.review-phase-boundaries` remains project-owned with `block_threshold: 0.90` and\n  `blocking_enabled: false`; verify with\n  `.venv/bin/pytest -q tests/unit/test_project_review_phase_boundaries.py`.\n- [ ] The diff-based criterion eval emits findings for `RP-F1..RP-F6` and none for\n  `RP-N1..RP-N6`. Across three runs, recall is `1.0`, false-accept is `0.0`, agreement is\n  `1.0`, minimum per-case stability is at least `2/3`, and Cohen kappa is at least `0.70`; verify with\n  `.venv/bin/rebar criteria eval project.review-phase-boundaries --runs 3 --output json`.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] Ticket `9447-b31c-e0b7-446d` records positive-control and negative-probe\n  Gerrit patchset SHAs and UTC timestamps on one change, plus the retained `code_review_result_v2`\n  payloads. The positive control has `coverage.llm_ran: true` and no\n  `project.review-phase-boundaries` entry in any verdict list; the negative finding carries the\n  project physical `reviewer_id`, logical criterion id, Pass-2 validity/impact answers, and\n  deterministic advisory Pass-3 fields; the final submitted revision removes the probe directive\n  and contains only phase-compliant instructions.\n- [ ] No child enables blocking or changes the threshold during this pilot; verify with\n  `.venv/bin/python -c 'import json; r=json.load(open(\".rebar/criteria_routing.json\"))[\"code_review\"][\"project.review-phase-boundaries\"]; assert r[\"block_threshold\"] == 0.90 and r[\"blocking_enabled\"] is False'`.","env_id":"reconciler","file_impact":[{"path":"src/rebar/llm/criteria/ids.py","reason":"Gate-keyed logical criterion-id to prompt-id mapping"},{"path":"src/rebar/llm/code_review/batch_runner.py","reason":"Exactly-once Round-A project-criterion fan-in"},{"path":"src/rebar/llm/code_review/workflow_ops.py","reason":"Repository-effective deterministic Pass-3 routing"},{"path":"src/rebar/llm/evals/eval_solver.py","reason":"Project criterion eval solver dispatch"},{"path":"src/rebar/llm/evals/eval.py","reason":"Gate-aware criterion calibration mapping"},{"path":"src/rebar/_cli/_llm_eval_commands.py","reason":"Resolve criterion gate at criteria-eval preflight"},{"path":".rebar/criteria_routing.json","reason":"Project criterion activation and advisory posture"},{"path":".rebar/prompts/code-review-project-review-phase-boundaries.md","reason":"Project-owned four-phase boundary rubric"},{"path":".rebar/evals/code-review-project-review-phase-boundaries.eval.yam